:Instructions
1,<b>StarWars Town Generator v1.1</b>
_<p>
_Welcome to the Town Generator!
_</p>
_<p>
_The parameters for this table are detailed below. If you wish to customize the table
_ for your campaign, refer to the instructions within the table file itself (accessible by
_ the "open book" button to the left, found between the d6 and the lightning bolt, or
_ "Edit Table" on the menu bar above).
_<ul>
_<li><b>Size of Town:</b> Select the size of the town you wish to generate with this parameter.
_ Larger settlements will, naturally, take longer to generate. "Random" will generate a random town,
_ which could be anything from a hamlet to a city. "View Instructions" will display these directions.</li>
_<li><b>Generate Name:</b> Use this to tell TableSmith to either generate a town name for you,
_ or to specify that you are going to enter one yourself.</li>
_<li><b>Enter Town Name:</b> If you selected "No" for the previous parameter, this is where you
_ enter the name of the town you are generating. This parameter is ignored if you selected "Yes"
_ previously.</li>
_<li><b>Maximum Number of Businesses:</b> Large towns, cities, etc. may have a <i>lot</i> of
_ businesses for each type (numerous cobblers, smiths, etc.). The amount of each will be displayed
_ in the results window, but it is likely you don't want to see the names and personalities of every
_ single business owner in your town. This option will tell TableSmith to show you, at most,
_ the number of businesses of each type that you specify (so, for example, the program may 
_ generate 76 barbers, but it will only display 15, or however many you want).</li>
_</ul>
_</p>
_<p>
_Most of what is generated is self-explantory. A few elements of a generated town that may be unclear
_ are explained below.
_<ul>
_<li><b>Personality:</b> Most of the business owners and other individuals listed will have a
_ personality displayed. This is for GMs, to help them role-play the merchant (or whoever) when dealing
_ with PCs. This can be ignored if the group doesn't care about such things.</li>
_<li><b>Quality:</b> This is a rating from one to three stars. One star is poor, two is average, three
_ is good. This is a general characteristic that the GM can apply however he sees fit. In mechanical terms,
_ this might mean that masterwork weapons or armor are only available from a "3-star" business, and
_ items from a "1-star" business might have a chance of breaking when used. The GM must decide how
_ she wishes to apply this value.
_<li><b>Buy/Sell Factor:</b> These are values that should be applied to the rulebook costs of things to
_ determine how much the merchant will buy or sell items at. The "Buy" factor (the first number) should
_ be multiplied by the rulebook cost to determine how much the merchant will pay for items of the
_ type they deal in. Likewise, the "Sell" factor should be used for items they are selling. Example: A
_ Parts Dealer would likely sell or buy parts. If his Buy/Sell Factor is 0.5 / 1.1, that means that he'll buy parts
_ at 50&#37; their base cost in the rulebooks, and he sells parts at 10&#37; over their base cost (1.1 or 110&#37;).
_</ul>
_</p>
_<p>
_Many of the generated items can be changed by clicking on them. If you see text in blue, click on it and
_ a new value will be generated (use this to change the names of businesses, their quality, their owner's
_ personality, etc.).
_</p>

